{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d823df24-7bbc-476b-970e-672ae714cd54","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK went up → workloads need to go up too → `dotnet workload update`.\n\nIf issues persist after updating, also try:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build --no-incremental\n```\n\nThe `--no-incremental` flag forces a clean rebuild, clearing any stale cached artifacts.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d2d4be59-04b6-4914-bd10-993229dbb6c1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general .NET knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":265,"requestId":"1433:2A9B4:6EBE32D:76FEAEF:6A03CC02"},"id":"c197a9a1-6291-48af-8a4a-e1a8e4378892","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:55:37.754Z","parentId":"6587179b-8cd2-4978-a7e3-501fb381ba94"}
